# Pulmonary Embolism and DVT (Anat, Pharm)

**Case:** *A 52-year-old woman suddenly developed breathlessness the day after laparoscopic cholecystectomy. The patient, who was previously otherwise well, had a strong family history of ischaemic heart disease and smoked 20 cigarettes per day. Examination revealed an obese, distressed woman with obvious tachypnoea and a non-productive cough. Auscultation of her chest revealed decreased air entry at the right base*

- DDx for dyspnoea
    - Respiratory
        - Airways
            - Obstructive diseases - asthma, COPD, bronchiectasis
            - Tumour
            - Anaphylaxis
            - Foreign body
        - Parenchyma
            - ILD
            - Pneumonia
            - Pulmonary oedema
            - Malignancy
        - Vasculature
            - PE
            - Pulmonary HTN
            - Vasculitis
            - Hepatopulmonary syndrome â†’ tends to improve when supine
        - Pleura
            - Effusion
            - Pneumothorax
    - Cardiovascular
        - Myocardium â†’ impaired filling or ejection leading to backward failure
            - Heart failure
            - Coronary artery disease or ACS
            - Valvulopathy
        - Pericardium â†’ increased pulmonary vascular filling pressures [may prevent with heart failure but no pro-BNP due to failure of dilation)
            - Constrictive
            - Tamponade
        - Electrical
            - Arrhythmias (dyspnoea due to failure of effective contraction)
    - Secondary problems (non-cardiorespiratory)
        - Chest wall
            - Flail chest
            - Kyphoscoliosis
            - Obesity
        - Neuromuscular
            - Myasthenia gravis
            - GBS
            - ALS
        - Haematology
            - Anaemia (impaired O2 delivery, may have normal O2 saturations)
        - Other
            - Acidosis â€”> tachypnoea to correct pH
            - Hyperthyroidism (increased T4)
            - Psychogenic â€”> anxiety
            - Deconditioning
- Sxs of PE
    - Potentially indicative of PE
        - Acute onset dyspnoea, chest pain (pleuritic)
        - Cough +/- haemoptysis
        - May have
            - Tachycardia, tachypnoea, hypoxia
            - Signs of DVT (unilateral leg swelling and tenderness)
    - Symptoms depend on the size of the embolus
        - 80% of PE are clinically silent (small and resolve) â€”> dual arterial supply of the lung parenchyma prevents infarction
        - Acute massive PE
            - Occlusion of pulmonary trunk and major circulatory collapse (loss of CO) â€”> hypotension, tachycardia and death
        - Acute small-medium PE â€”> occlusion of segmental artery â€”> infarction
            - Haemoptysis, pleuritic chest pain
        - Chronic small PE â€”> remodelling and scarring leads to pulmonary hypertension and right heart failure
    - Categorising PE
        - Timing
            - Acute, subacute, chronic
        - Haemodynamic stability
            - Unstable = hypotension
                - Defined as SBP < 90 or drop of > 40 from baseline for a period of > 15 min
            - Stable
                - Submassive PE can cause signs of RV dysfunction or borderline circulatory instability which stabilises with fluid therapy
                - Can be mildly asymptomatic
- RFs for PE
    - PMHx of previous DVT/PE
    - Related to the causes of venous thrombosis (Virchowâ€™s triad)
        - Changes in blood flow (venous stasis)
            - Immobilisation (bedrest, long air travel, disability)
            - Cardiac insufficiency (advanced CHF, AMI)
            - Chronic venous insufficiency
        - Changes in coagulability (hypercoagulability)
            - Inherited
                - Factor V Leiden
                    - Mutation which prevents Protein C effectively binding
                - Protein C or S deficiency
                    - Note: Protein C normally inactivates factor V and VIII (S is a co-factor)
                - Antithrombin III deficiency
            - Acquired
                - Inflammatory state (post trauma, post surgery)
                - Malignancy
                - Hyperoestrogenic states (obesity, HRT, COCP, pregnancy)
        - Changes in vessel wall (endothelial injury)
            - Smoking
            - HTN
            - Atherosclerosis
            - Iatrogenic (indwelling venous lines)
- Ix approach for PE
    - Begin with a comprehensive cardiorespiratory examination
        - Concurrent assessment and resuscitation if needed
        - If the patient is haemodynamically unstable, urgent TTE and CTPA
    - For the haemodynamically stable patient (non-pregnant, no anticoagulants in the last 72h), **Wellsâ€™ criteria to establish Pre-test probability** and guide investigative workup
        - Wells Criteria
            - Small Little TIP About Clots
                - Suspected DVT (signs and symptoms) [3]
                - Likely PE [3]
                - Tachycardia (1.5)
                - Immobilisation or recent surgery (>3 days) in past 4wks (1.5)
                - PMHx of VTE (DVT, PE) (1.5)
                - Active malignancy (1)
                - Coughing up blood (haemoptysis) (1)
            - Two-tier approach: Unlikely (â‰¤4), likely (>4)
            - Three-tier: low (<2), moderate (2-6), high (>6)
    - Approach
        - Low probability or unlikely
            - PERC rule (1 point for each)
                - Age > 50
                - Signs
                    - Tachycardia (HR > 100)
                    - SpO2 < 95% RA
                    - Unilateral leg swelling
                    - Haemoptysis
                - History
                    - Prior VTE
                - Risk factors
                    - Recent surgery or trauma (<4 weeks)
                    - Hyper-oestrogenic state
            - If PERC is 1 or more, D-dimer (high NPPV - sensitive but not specific)
        - Moderate-high or likely, investigate with CTPA
            - If CTPA is not available or contraindicated (e.g. CKD and contrast, previous allergy), use V/Q scan
            - Commence anticoagulation if imaging not possible
    - Ancillary Ix
        - Bedside
            - ECG â†’ S1Q3T3 characteristic finding
            - Blood gas (expect hypoxaemia, respiratory alkalosis due to hyperventilation)
        - Bloods
            - FBC
            - UEC and LFT (baseline measurements, guide management if underlying organ dysfunction)
            - Coagulation panel
                - aPPT â†’ intrinsic and common pathway (assess heparin therapy)
                - PT â†’ extrinsic and common pathway (assess warfarin with INR)
            - D-dimer
            - Troponins (identify cardiac aetiology)
        - Imaging
            - CXR (rule out DDx)
            - CTPA or V/Q scan
            - Lower limb Doppler U/S (or compressive U/S) to diagnose DVT
    - ECG findings in PE
        - Baseline ECG important and used to rule out DDx
        - Possible findings
            - Most common: sinus tachycardia, non-specific ST segment and T wave changes
            - Other changes
                - Atrial tachyarrhythmias (AF, atrial flutter)
                - S1Q3T3 (deep S wave in 1, Q wave, inverted T wave in 3)
                - New RBB
                - Right axis deviation
    - CXR findings in PE
        - Often normal in PE - useful to rule out DDx
        - Possible findings
            - Hamptonâ€™s hump: rounded infarct wedge (distal as the proximal portion receives collateral circulation)
            - Westernmarkâ€™s sign: area of increased radiolucency (relative oligaemia) distal to an occluded artery
            - Dilated central pulmonary artery (Fleischnerâ€™s sign)
            - Dilated right descending pulmonary artery (Pallaâ€™s sign)

*A chest X-ray showed an area of opacification at the right base, together with a small right pleural effusion.*

- ABG interpretation
    
    ![Screenshot 2025-06-23 at 1.41.46â€¯PM.png](Pulmonary%20Embolism%20and%20DVT%20(Anat,%20Pharm)%201300acf2446a81df9c93fdb0badc5ef5/Screenshot_2025-06-23_at_1.41.46_PM.png)
    
    - In an acute PE, hypoxaemia (V/Q mismatch) and hypocapnia (hyperventilation) are possible
    - Physiology
        - Embolus decreases blood flow to ventilated areas (unable to gas exchange â†’hypoxia and hypercapnia)
        - Elevated CO2 detected by central chemoreceptors (medulla) + 
        Low O2 detected by peripheral chemoreceptors (carotid and aortic bodies) =
        **Stimulates resp â†’ hyperventilation â†’ hypocapnia**
        - Renal compensation not adequate in acute setting
- Management of PE and VTE
    - Treatment goal
        1. Patient stabilisation
        2. Prevent further clot expansion, embolism and infarction
        3. Address underlying risk factors
    - Immediate treatment
        - Stabilisation
            - Conduct a primary survey using A-E framework and commence supportive therapy
                - Respiratory support â†’ supp O2 and escalate as necessary
                - Haemodynamic support
                    - IV fluid resus (gentle bolus to avoid fluid overload and RV strain)
                    - Vasopressor support if non-responsive
                - Analgesia
    - Definitive therapy (anticoagulation)
        - Unstable patient suggesting massive PE
            - Fibrinolysis (alteplase) OR surgical embolectomy if contraindicated for thrombolysis
            - Follow up with anticoagulation
        - Stable patient
            - Anticoagulation
                - Oral Factor Xa inhibitors (rivaroxaban, apixaban)
                    - Note: dabigatran also requires bridging anticoagulation
                - LMWH (preferred in cancer or pregnancy)
                - UFH (when LMWH is contraindicated â€”> CKD, emergency surgery as reversible with protamine)
                - Warfarin (requires bridging dose as there is a delay in depletion of vitamin-K dependent factors)
            - Decision on the best agent is based on clinical experience and balancing bleeding risks and patient factors (comorbidities, cost, convenience)
            - If patient is contraindicated to any anticoagulant â€”> IVC filter
    - Long-term management
        - Ongoing anticoagulant (minimum of three months unless multiple unprovoked episodes or other risk factors)
        - NOACs or warfarin preferred (oral agents)
    - Preventative management
        - Compression stockings, TED stockings
        - Early ambulation
        - Manage risk factors for secondary prevention (e.g. cease smoking, weight control)
- Pathophysiology of PE
    - Pulmonary emboli are most commonly thromboembolic however there may be other sources. These cause obstruction of pulmonary vasculature and subsequent infarction
        - May be fat emboli (trauma, long bone fracture), air emboli (often iatrogenic), septic emboli (e.g. infective endocarditis), amniotic fluid
    - Most common source of thromboembolism is DVT
        - DVT can form in favourable conditions (Virchowâ€™s triad)
            - Propagates in the direction of blood flow and can dislodge into pulmonary circulation
        - The consequences of an impacted embolus depend on the size of the embolus
- Pathology - autopsy findings
    - Note: autopsy may be conducted at the Coronerâ€™s discretion if the cause of death is not reasonably known
        - If a cause of death cannot be reasonable ascribed, refer to Coroner
        - Patientâ€™s may request a hospital autopsy without Coroner input
    - Findings
        - Lower limbs
            - Thrombi in the deep veins (may propagate into larger proximal veins)
                - Often in iliac, femoral, popliteal veins
                - Laminated venous thrombus (supports in-situ formation)
        - Lungs
            - Multiple pulmonary thromboemboli
            - Area of haemorrhagic infarction (red, wedge-shaped) â†’ may not be infarcted if sudden death
            - Fibrous exudate on pleural surface
        - Cardiovascular
            - Massive thromboembolus in pulmonary or lobar artery
- Complications of PE and DVT
    - PE
        - Acute: pulmonary infarction (medium), obstructive shock and sudden death (massive)
        - Chronic
            - Recurrent emboli
            - Pulmonary hypertension (chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension) â€”> class 4
                - Reorganisation of recurrent emboli leads to smooth muscle proliferation and scarring
                    - Increases pulmonary vascular resistance and decreased flow
                    - Increases afterload on right heart â€”> RVH and cor pulmonale
    - DVT
        - Acute
            - Most common outcome is lysis and restoration of normal flow
            - Pulmonary embolus (50% of proximal DVTs)
            - Phlegmasia cerulea dolens (painful, blue, swollen leg)
                - Major venous obstruction resulting in severe oedema due to congestion
                    - Comprises arterial supply and nerve function
                - Indication for urgent venous thrombectomy
        - Chronic
            - Chronic venous insufficiency â€”> congestion
                - Venous dilatation and varicose veins
                - Skin changes (haemosiderin deposition and lipodermatosclerosis)
                - Venous ulcers (poor healing, shallow, necrotic base)

### Memorandum (Pharm)

[](data:image/png;base64,)

*A 30-year-old female presents to the emergency department 3 weeks post-partum with pleuritic chest pain.*

- Approach to Hx and Exam
    - If signs of haemodynamic instability, first priority would be to conduct a primary survey and initiate appropriate resuscitation as needed via an A-E framework
        - Airway (assess patency, provide support and remove any obstructions)
        - Breathing (assess RR, apparent WOB, SpO2 and administer supplementary O2)
        - Circulation (HR, SBP, prepare fluid resuscitation and vasopressor support as needed)
        - Disability (GCS)
        - Exposure (temperature, systemic signs (e.g. rash))
    - History
        - HOPC
            - Respiratory symptoms (dyspnoea, cough, chest pain)
            - DVT symptoms (pain, swelling, redness, onset, risk factors)
            - Constitutional symptoms (signs of malignancy, TB)
            - Characterise onset
        - PMHx
            - Risk factors for thrombosis (previous VTE, cancer, pregnancy, recent immbolisation or surgery)
            - Existing medical conditions (cardiorespiratory disease, renal disease)
        - Medications and allergies
        - Family history (thrombotic disease, clotting disorders)
        - Social history
            - Smoking, occupational exposure, travel
    - Examination
        - Conduct a full cardiovascular, respiratory and peripheral vascular examination
            - Start with a general inspection and measuring vital signs
    - Determine pre-test probability with Wellâ€™s criteria
        - Not validated in pregnant women and it is important to have a low index of suspicion for VTE
            - Note: post-partum period is classified as non-pregnant
        - Proceed to CTPA if suspicious of PE, D-dimer is low suspicion
- Anticoagulant drugs
    - Unfractionated heparin
        - Mechanism
            - Potentiates anti-thrombin III â€”> inhibits thrombin and Factor Xa
        - Adverse effects
            - Bleeding (greatest risk in first 3 months)
            - Heparin induced thrombocytopaenia (and HITT) (2.5%)
            - Osteoporosis (long-term use)
        - Contraindications
            - Active pathological bleeding
            - Hypersensitivity
        - Monitoring
            - aPTT every 4-6 hours until therapeutic levels reached (1.5-2x baseline)
        - Reversal: protamine sulfate
        - Note: safe in pregnancy and renal disease (although LMWH preferred in pregnancy)
            - Short half life (good in peri-operative period)
    - LMWH
        - Mechanism: potentiates antithrombin III â€”> preferential inhibition of Factor Xa
            - Less effect on thrombin inhibition
        - Adverse effects
            - Bleeding
            - Less risk of HIT
        - Contraindications
            - Bleeding
            - Dose adjustment in renal impairment
        - Monitoring - usually not required but can monitor anti-Xa levels
        - Note: longer half-life than UFH
            - Reversible with protamine sulfate
            - Preferred in pregnancy, malignancy
    - Warfarin
        - Mechanism: inhibits Vitamin K epoxide reductase â€”> blocks activation of vitamin K
            - Prevents synthesis of vitamin K dependent clotting factors (2, 7, 9, 10, C, S)
            - May have an early pro-thrombotic effect (inhibition of Protein C and S) and needs bridging to establish a stable therapeutic INR â‰¥ 2 for â‰¥ 2 days
            - Drug contains stereoisomers of warfarin (mixture of R and S)
        - Adverse effects
            - Haemorrhage
            - Teratogenic effects (stillbirth, congenital heart defects)
            - Rare: rash, nausea and vomiting, skin necrosis (initial prothrombotic effect and microthrombi formation)
            - Osteoporosis with long term use
        - Contraindications
            - Pregnancy
            - Active pathological bleeding
            - Multiple drug-drug interactions
        - Monitor with INR between 2-3
        - Reversal
            - Vitamin K
            - Fresh frozen plasma
            - Prothrombinex (concentrate of clotting factors)
    - Direct thrombin inhibitors
        - E.g. dabigatran
        - Mechanism: direct inhibition of thrombin
            - Note: thrombin normally cleaves fibrinogen â€”> fibrin
                - Also promotes platelet activation and aggregation, activates factors V, VIII, XI, XIII
        - Adverse effects: bleeding, hepatotoxicity, GI symptoms
        - Contraindications
            - Serious hypersensitivity
            - Active pathological bleeding
            - Severe renal impairment
        - No routine monitoring required
        - Reversal
            - Idarucizumab
    - Direct Factor Xa inhibitors
        - E.g. apixaban, rivaroxaban
        - Mechanism: direct inhibition of factor Xa (normally converts prothrombin â€”> thrombin)
        - Adverse effects
            - Bleeding
        - Contraindications
            - Severe hypersensitivity
            - Active pathological bleeding
            - Severe liver impairment
        - Monitoring
            - Routine monitoring not required
        - Reversal
            - Andexanet alfa (expensive, use in emergencies)
- Fibrinolytics
    - Mechanism: serine protease which binds to fibrin in a clot and activates plasminogen
        - Converts plasminogen to plasmin â€”> increasded fibrin degredation
    - Adverse effects
        - Bleeding
- Monitoring heparin vs warfarin
    - Unfractionated heparin
        - aPPT
            - Goal: 1.5-2x baseline
            - Initially monitor every 4-6h, then every 24h once aPPT has stabilised
        - Monitor platelets at baseline and every 2nd day from day 4 - 14 for HIT
    - LMWH
        - Usually does not need monitoring
        - Anti-Xa levels (in certain clinical scenarios)
        - Platelets
    - Warfarin
        - INR (target 2-3 or higher in mechanical heart valve parients)
        - Timeline of monitoring varies depending on risk of thrombotic events
            - Initially weekly (low risk) and daily (high risk)
- Interactions of warfarin
    - Warfarin is metabolised by CYP450 enzymes in the liver
        - Drugs which cause CYP induction (decrease INR)
            - St. Johnâ€™s wort
            - Glucocorticoids
            - Carbamazepine
            - Sulphonylureas (potentiated by warfarin)
            - Rifampicin
        - Drugs which cause CYP inhibition (increase INR)
            - SSRIs
            - Amiodarone
            - Metronidazole
        - Can be affected by bile sequestrants (warfarin is lipid soluble), antiplatelets (increased bleeding risk)
- CIs for thrombolysis
    - Absolute
        - Active bleeding or known bleeding risk
        - Intracranial
            - Previous haemorrhage
            - Recent history of ischaemic stroke, intracranial or spinal surgery or trauma (<3 months)
            - Known intracranial neoplasm, aneurysm, AVM
        - Severe uncontrolled hypertension
    - Relative
        - Recent major surgery
        - Recent non-serious head trauma
        - Recent LP or arterial puncture at non-compressible site
        - Hepatic or renal dysfunction
        - Pregnancy
- Relationship of PE w/ COCP
    - Oestrogen is pro-thrombotic and increases clotting factor production
    - Recommend for patient to change to an alternative method of contraception
        - E.g. progesterone-only pill, mirena or copper IUD, implanon, barrier protection

### Memorandum: (Pharm) DVT

**Case:**

*A 56-year-old woman with a history of T2DM noticed increasing pain and swelling in her right calf after a hip replacement surgery. Examination revealed an obese woman with distinctive swelling of the right calf. Vitals showed hypertension and tachypnoea.*

- DDx for unilateral leg pain and swelling
    - Unilateral swelling
        - Exudate (non-pitting)
            - Cellulitis
            - Septic arthritis
            - Lymphoedema
        - Transudate (pitting oedema)
            - DVT
            - Venous compression (secondary to obstructive proximal mass)
            - Note: RHF, cirrhosis, nephrotic syndrome cause bilateral swelling
    - Mass
        - Haematoma of calf muscle
    - Leg pain
        - Muscular
            - Compartment syndrome
            - Myositis (more likely bilateral)
        - Skeletal
            - Osteomyelitis
            - Trauma
- Heritability of DVT
    - Family history of DVT increases the risk
        - A DVT in a first degree relative < 50 suggests the possibility of a hereditary susceptibility to thrombosis
    - Consider testing for the major inherited thrombophilias
        - Factor V Leiden mutation
        - Protein C or S deficiency
        - Antithrombin III deficiency
- Ix approach to DVT
    - Assess haemodynamic stability and vital signs given suspicion of DVT and PE
    - Primary diagnostic investigations
        - Clinical assessment and pre-test probability through modified Wellâ€™s score (DVT)
            - Low risk (â‰¤ 2) â€”> D-dimer
                - If D-dimer normal â€”> no further testing
                - If positive â€”> proceed to lower limb compression U/S with Doppler
            - High risk (>2)
                - Compression ultrasound with Doppler of lower limb
                    - Assesses blood flow (Doppler effect) and extent of the clot
                        - In DVT: reduced or absent blood flow, echogenic band and non-compressible venous segment
    - Ancillary investigations
        - Bedside
            - ECG (PE)
            - Blood gas (PE)
            - Consider B-hCG (pregnancy)
        - Labs
            - FBC, coags, UEC/LFT (baseline), B-hCG
            - Skin swab if considering cellulitis
        - Imaging
            - Consider contrast enhanced CT or MR venography (if uncertainty around IVC thrombosis)
            - CTPA if indicated for PE (Wellâ€™s criteria)
    - Modified DVT Wellâ€™s score
        - One point for the following
            - Signs of DVT
                - Paralysis, paresis or plaster of lower limb
                - Localised tenderness along deep venous system
                - Entire leg swollen
                - Calf swelling > 3cm compared to normal side
                - Collateral superficial veins
                - Pitting oedema on affected side
            - Active cancer, treatment or palliation in last 6 months
            - More than three days immobilisation or surgery in past 4 weeks
            - Previous DVT (Modified)
        - Subtract 2 points if alternative diagnosis likely or more likely than DVT
        - Evaluation (Modified)
            - â‰¥2 = likely DVT
- Duplex US - approach and findings
    - Approach
        - Consent the patient
        - Clean the skin
        - Apply conductive gel to the transducer
        - Pass the transducer over the skin until a blood vessel is identified
            - Veins should collapse on compression while arteries appear pulsatile
    - Mechanism
        - Uses sound waves to detect the movement of blood cells and visualise soft tissue
        - Transducer sends and receives sound waves which are amplified through a microphone
            - The sound waves rebound off from solid objects (e.g. blood cells). Movement of these objects cause a change in pitch of the reflected sound waves (can calculate speed and direction as per Doppler effect)
                - A thrombus = no blood flow = no pitch change
    - Findings
        - Non-compressible venous segment
        - Echogenic band inside non-compressible vein (thrombus)
        - Reduced or absent colour flow
            - Lack of flow augmentation on calf squeeze
    - Limitations
        - Cannot image iliac veins
        - May have difficulties in patients with obesity, severe oedema or casts
- Indications for anticoagulation in DVT
    - Anatomical: anticoagulation is indicated depending on the clotâ€™s location relative to the knee
        - Above the knee â€”> anticoagulate unless contraindicated
        - Below the knee â€”> consider anticoagulation (e.g. if provoking factors)
    - Treatment
        - Aims of DVT treatment include prevention of clot extension, embolisation or recurrence
        - Initial anticoagulation (first 10 days) â€”> decrease embolisation risk
            - Oral Factor Xa inhibitors
            - LMWH
            - LMWH and warfarin (outpatient management)
        - Long term anticoagulation (minimum 3 months assuming no provoking events)
- ABI (ankle brachial index)
    - ABI: measure of the ratio of SBP in ankle to SBP in arm
        - Used in the diagnosis of peripheral arterial disease
    - Method
        - Uses a Doppler probe to detect pulsatile flow
            - Inflate BP cuff until pulse stops and slowly deflate to observe for return of flow
            - Dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial in each foot (take larger value)
        - Compare to brachial artery BP (take larger pressure)
    - Interpretation
        - <0.9 = narrowing or blocking or arteries in leg
        - >1.2 = inconclusive (may suggest vessel hardening or calcification in PVD)
- Stereoisomers of warfarin
    - Warfarin is produced as a racemic mixture (mixture of equal chiral isomers) of R-Warfarin and S-Warfarin
        - S-Warfarin is 3-5x more potent in producing an anticoagulant response
        - Cleared through different CYP pathways
- Complications of heparin therapy
    - Heparin-induced thrombocytopaenia is a rare and potentially fatal complication of heparin exposure
        - Occurs around day 5-10
        - There is a benign type 1 HIT which is a non-immunological drop which occurs in the first 1-2 days following therapy initation
    - Pathophysiology
        - Heparin binds to platelet factor 4
            - Development of IgG antibodies against heparin-PF4 complex
            - Results in platelet activation, aggregation and microthrombi formation â€”> platelet consumption
        - Can progress to heparin induced thrombotic thrombocytopaenia
        - Can be identified early by platelet assays (do not count activated platelets)
    - Diagnosis of HIT
        - 4Tâ€™s score
            - Thrombocytopaenia (platelet â‰¥ 50% fall)
            - Timing (onset between 5-10 days)
            - Thrombosis (new, skin necrosis, acute systemic reaction)
            - Rule out other causes of thrombocytopaenia
        - HIT antibody testing (ELISA)
        - Serotonin release assay (measures platelet activation)
    - Treatment of HIT
        - Cease heparin immediately
        - Switch to a non-heparin anticoagulant (fondaparinaux, DOACs, danaparoid)
        - Monitor with anti-Factor Xa essay
        - Start oral agent (warfarin) when bridging agent at therapeutic levels and platelets > 150 000/microL
- How is heparin and warfarin reversed
    - Heparin â€”> protamine sulfate
    - Warfarin â€”> vitamin K, prothrombin complex concentrate + FFP
    - Dabigatran â€”> idarucizumab
    - Apixaban, rivaroxaban â€”> andexanet alfa
- What would instigate you to convert to a diff. anticoagulant
    - Warfarin â€”> DOAC
        - Poor compliance to medicine or INR monitoring
        - Adverse effects, new contraindication
        - Patient preference
    - DOAC â€”> warfarin
        - New renal or liver impairment
        - Need for a reversal agent
